+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| CS Programs Changing to Attract Women Students                     |
|   from the too-much-y-already dept.                                |
|   posted by Zonk on Tuesday April 17, @10:47 (United States)       |
|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/17/1335258           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Magnifico writes "The New York times is running an article about a push
by American universities to [0]actively recruit women into Computer
Science courses. The story, 'Computer Science Takes Steps to Bring Women
to the Fold', explains that the number of women in CS is shrinking:
'Women received about 38 percent of the computer science bachelor's
degrees awarded in the United States in 1985, the peak year, but in 2003,
the figure was only about 28 percent, according to the National Science
Foundation.' One of the largest barriers to recruiting women to the field
is the nerd factor. To attract women students to the CS field, 'Moving
emphasis away from programming proficiency was a key to the success of
programs Dr. Blum and her colleagues at Carnegie Mellon instituted to
draw more women into computer science.' Changes at CMU increased women
students in the CS program from 8 percent to nearly 40 percent."

Discuss this story at:
    http://it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/17/1335258

Links:
    0. http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/17/science/17comp.html?8dpc


